## Workflow

### Gate before commit / PR (always present — shipped by this installer)

Before every commit or PR, run the gate this installer actually ships:

- **`./scripts/audit-ai-docs.sh`** — drift + code-vs-docs probes (~10 sec). Run it before you commit.
- **`./scripts/check-rule-globs.sh`** — fails if a custom ESLint rule (R2 always; R7/R8 under `AIF_STRICT_RUNTIME=1`) matches **zero** source files, i.e. is silently inert against your layout. **Wired into `npm run validate` and the shipped CI `lint` job** — a layout the globs miss now fails loudly instead of silently shipping. If it fires, widen `RULE_GLOBS` in `eslint.config.mjs` to cover your layout (a flat / inline-router server whose routes live in `app.ts` with no `routes/` folder needs a broader boundary glob, e.g. `apps/*/src/**`). **Monorepos:** if a workspace package ships its own `eslint.config.*`, ESLint's nearest-config resolution means the AIF root config never governs that package. The gate accounts for this: a shadowing package is pruned from the root probe (so a file there can't fake a green) and checked separately — if it has boundary files but its config does **not** wire R2 it **FAILS** (copy the custom-rule block into, or re-export the root config from, that package); if it re-exports/extends another config it **WARNs** (verify R2 is inherited). **Brownfield CI:** install never overwrites a pre-existing `.github/workflows/ci.yml`, so on an existing repo the gate may run only in `npm run validate`; install prints a WARN when no workflow wires it — add `- run: bash scripts/check-rule-globs.sh` to your lint job.
- **`./scripts/check-lintstaged-resolves.sh`** — fails if a `.lintstagedrc.json` command's binary (e.g. `eslint`) can't resolve from the directory lint-staged would run it in. **Monorepos:** a single root config runs `eslint` from the repo root, where a per-package binary isn't installed → `ENOENT` blocks the commit. Fix: keep a per-package `.lintstagedrc.json` beside each package (install drops one for packages present at install time). Run after `npm/pnpm install`.
- The **pre-push hook** (`.husky/pre-push`) fires automatically on `git push` — typecheck, `vitest related`, dependency-cruiser.
- **CI** gates the PR (`ci-success` required check). This is the last-resort authority that does not depend on local tooling.

These are unconditional — they ship with the project and need no extra install.

**Runtime-discipline rules R7/R8 are opt-in.** `no-direct-time-randomness` (R7) and `require-otel-span` (R8) need an injected Clock/Random + `infrastructure/` layer and an OpenTelemetry tracer — infra a fresh skeleton lacks. The shipped `eslint.config.mjs` enables them only when `AIF_STRICT_RUNTIME=1` is set in the environment; R2 (validation at boundaries) stays unconditional. Custom-rule file globs are **layout-agnostic** (flat / layered / monorepo) — widen `RULE_GLOBS` in `eslint.config.mjs` if `check-rule-globs.sh` reports a rule inert.

### AI Factory commands (only if you have aif installed)

**If you use AI Factory (aif)** for spec-driven development, the commands below are available. AI Factory is **not bundled** by this installer — install it separately to use them.

- **`/aif-explore <task>`** — when scope is unclear. Saves research to `.ai-factory/RESEARCH.md`.
- **`/aif-plan <task>`** — for any non-trivial change. Creates branch, writes plan to `.ai-factory/plans/`.
- **`/aif-implement`** — execute plan step by step with checkpoints.
- **`/aif-verify`** — _if you use aif_, runs `review-sidecar`, `living-docs-auditor` over RULES.md and the audit-ai-docs probes. A convenience wrapper around the unconditional gate above — not a substitute for it.
- **`/aif-fix <error>`** — targeted bug fix. Reads the plan, knows exactly what was intended.
- **`/aif-commit`** — final commit, groups checkpoint commits, pushes.

### Forbidden

- `git commit --no-verify` — bypassing pre-commit/pre-push hooks.
- `git push -f` to `main`.
- Skipping `./scripts/audit-ai-docs.sh` / the pre-push hook before PR.
- Adding rules to AGENTS.md / RULES.md without a measurable check.

## Orchestration — backlog & /pipeline

> Where multi-step work is planned and prioritised. The `/pipeline` skill reads these.

- **Kickoffs / handoffs** (one task-brief per work item) live at:
  `.ai-factory/orchestrator-prompts/<work-item-name>/kickoff.md`
- **Backlog plan** (priority registry across all work items) lives at:
  `.ai-factory/orchestrator-prompts/plan.md` — `/pipeline` **creates it on first run** if absent.
- **`/pipeline`** (Claude Code; manual workflow on other harnesses) reads the kickoffs + plan,
  ranks them, and emits a launch-table telling you what to start next. An **empty** backlog
  (no kickoffs yet) is normal — it reports "nothing queued", not an error.
- **Kickoff format:** a markdown file beginning with a `Type:` line (`fix` / `research` /
  `feature`), the goal, and — if the work splits into parallel sub-steps — a `## §1 Sub-wave`
  section with one table row per sub-step. Without sub-steps, a plain task brief is fine.

These paths are harness-agnostic (`.ai-factory/`, not `.claude/`) so the backlog is portable
across Claude Code / Cursor / Codex / Aider.

## Skills available

The following skills auto-activate on relevant queries:

- **`rules-as-tests`** — five-layer framework (architecture / meta-tests / spec by example / mutation / living docs). Auto-triggers on questions about ESLint, Stryker, Pact, dependency-cruiser, AI-driven code drift.
- **`tool-bootstrapping`** — when project deps change, analyses stack for MCP/skill fit, proposes a confirmation list, persists accepted/rejected decisions in `.ai-factory/tool-decisions.md`. Auto-triggers on MCP, skill-discovery, bootstrapping, and tool-decision queries.

Add additional project skills here as you create them. Don't list a skill until its file is committed (see ai-traps.md, lesson #2).

## Sub-agents (Claude Code)

Loaded by AI Factory in `.claude/agents/`:

- **`review-sidecar`** — two-AI tautology review. Reads tests as if external reviewer with no memory of how they were written.
- **`living-docs-auditor`** — runs `scripts/audit-ai-docs.sh` (drift detection + code-vs-docs probes). Interprets PASS/FAIL.

## Test commands

Core test commands — shipped for **every** stack (`install.sh` adds these to `package.json`):

```bash
npm run test                       # vitest run (unit + audit tests)
npm run test:watch                 # vitest watch mode
npm run test:coverage              # with coverage thresholds
npm run test:integration           # *.integration.ts files (real DB)
npm run test:mutation              # Stryker — full run (all files)
npm run test:mutation:incremental  # Stryker — changed files only (the PR-diff gate)
```

### UI projects (react-next stack) — only if you installed Storybook / Playwright

**Not shipped by default.** `install.sh react-next` ships `playwright.config.ts`, but no `npm run` script and no `@playwright/test` dependency; Storybook is never scaffolded. Install the tooling yourself first, then add these:

```bash
npm run test-storybook             # Storybook test runner — needs @storybook/test-runner
npx playwright test                # E2E — react-next config only; needs @playwright/test
```

## Validate everything

```bash
npm run validate                # typecheck + lint + format:check + arch:check + audit:docs + test (parallel)
./scripts/audit-ai-docs.sh     # drift + code-vs-docs probes (~10 sec)
```

## Stack constraints (enforced)

- TypeScript strict + `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`.
- Node.js version pinned in `.nvmrc` — CI depends on it.
- ESLint 10 flat config — see `eslint.config.mjs`.
- Mutation kill rate ≥70% on PR diff (Stryker incremental).
- Coverage thresholds per-module (see `vitest.config.ts`).
- Architecture rules in `.dependency-cruiser.cjs` — fail on violation.

## Files NOT to edit without explicit reason

- `.ai-factory/RULES.md` — rules are added/changed via PR with rationale, not silently.
- `.dependency-cruiser.cjs` — same.
- `eslint.config.mjs` — same.
- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` — same.
- `scripts/audit-ai-docs.sh` — additions need a paired negative test (see references/self-testing-docs.md).

